{"cursor":"5969","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"'The Maxims of Ptahhotep' or 'Instruction of Ptahhotep' is an ancient literary\nwork attributed to Ptahhotep, a vizier under King Isesi of the Egyptian Fifth\nDynasty (ca. 2414-2375 BC). Nicholas Grimal, A History of Ancient Egypt,\n1992 Blackwell Publishing, p.79 It is a collection of maxims and advice in\nthe [[sebayt]] genre on human relations, that are directed to his son. The work\nsurvives today in papyrus copies, including the Prisse Papyrus which dates from\nthe Middle Kingdom and is on display at the BibliothÃ¨que Nationale in Paris.\nThere are considerable differences between the Prisse Papyrus version and the\ntwo texts at the British Museum. M. Lichtheim, Ancient Egyptian Literature,\nVol.I, p.61\n\nIn the introduction, the author explains the reason for writing the\ninstruction, namely his having reached old age and wanting to pass on the\nwisdom of his ancestors who had, in his words, listened to the\ngods. Lichtheim op. cit. p.63 The Maxims are conformist precepts\nextolling such civil virtues as truthfulness, self-control and kindness towards\none's fellow beings. Learning by listening to everybody and knowing that human\nknowledge is never perfect are a leitmotif. FranÃ§oise Dunand, Christiane\nZivie-Coche, Gods and Men in Egypt: 3.000 BCE to 395 CE, Cornell University\nPress 2004, p.148  Avoiding open conflict wherever possible should not be\nconsidered weakness. Justice should be pursued and in the end it will be a\ngod's command that prevails. Lichtheim op. cit. p.65 Some of the\nmaxims refer to one's behaviour when in the presence of the great, how to\nchoose the right master and how to serve him. Others teach the correct way to\nlead through openness and kindness. Greed is the base of all evil and should be\nguarded against, while generosity towards family and friends is\npraiseworthy. Lichtheim op. cit. p.68 Rise in the social order should\nbe accepted as a gift from an Egyptian god Lichtheim op. cit. p.72\nand could be preserved by accepting the precedence of one's superior.\n","linknr":119,"url":"The_Maxims_of_Ptahhotep","recorded":1372152817,"links":["/w/index.php?title=The_Maxims_of_Ptahhotep&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=The_Maxims_of_Ptahhotep&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","#mw-navigation","#p-search","/wiki/Ptahhotep","/wiki/Vizier","/wiki/Isesi","/wiki/Egypt","/wiki/Fifth_Dynasty","#cite_note-1","/wiki/Sebayt","/wiki/Papyrus","/wiki/Prisse_Papyrus","/wiki/Biblioth%C3%A8que_nationale_de_France","/wiki/British_Museum","#cite_note-2","#cite_note-3","#cite_note-4","/wiki/Egyptian_pantheon","#cite_note-5","#cite_note-6","/wiki/Egyptian_pantheon","#cite_note-7","#Selected_passages","#See_also","#References","#External_links","/w/index.php?title=The_Maxims_of_Ptahhotep&action=edit&section=1","/wiki/Christian_Jacq","#cite_note-8","/wiki/Maat","/w/index.php?title=The_Maxims_of_Ptahhotep&action=edit&section=2","/wiki/Instructions_of_Kagemni","/w/index.php?title=The_Maxims_of_Ptahhotep&action=edit&section=3","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d6/Wikiquote-logo-en.svg/40px-Wikiquote-logo-en.svg.png","//en.wikiquote.org/wiki/Ptahhotep","#cite_ref-1","#cite_ref-2","/wiki/M._Lichtheim","#cite_ref